    "Background": {
      "text": "Most common SBI, accounts for 5-8% of children presenting for fever without clear source\nAssociated with bacteremia in up to 30% of infants 4-8wk of age\nE. coli\nis responsible for ~80% of UTIs\nAfter 1yr of age, occult UTI with normal UA extremely rare\nAfter 2yr of age, UTI remains common in girls (but associated with symptoms)\nUTI in adolescent girl is suggestive of intercourse\nPrevalence of UTI in\nbronchiolitis\nis only 0.8% based on 2019 meta-analysis, which is far lower than in previous studies, suggesting less need for automatic testing for UTI in bronchiolitis\n[1]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "E. coli",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/E._coli"
        },
